\u20131\n|match_\u017dEL_TET=6\u20130\n|match_\u017dEL_VAR=4\u20132\n|match_\u017dEL_VEL=2\u20130\n|match_\u017dEL_VOJ=2\u20131\n|match_\u017dEL_ZAG=2\u20130\n\n|update= \n|source=\n}}\n\n==Season statistics==\n*Widest winning margin: '''7 goals''':\n**Dinamo Zagreb 7\u20130 NK Zagreb (13 September 1981)\n**Hajduk Split 7\u20130 Teteks (31 March 1982)\n*Most goals in a match: '''9 goals''':\n**Rijeka 5\u20134 Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161 (23 August 1981)\n**Partizan 7\u20132 Sloboda (25 April 1982)\n\n==See also==\n*[[1981\u201382 Yugoslav Second League]]\n*[[1981\u201382 Yugoslav Cup]]\n*[[1981\u201382 NK Dinamo Zagreb season]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joeghist.html Yugoslavia Domestic Football Full Tables]\n\n{{Yugoslav First League}}\n{{1981\u201382 in European Football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1981-82 Yugoslav First League}}\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League seasons]]\n[[Category:1981\u201382 in European association football leagues|Yugo]]\n[[Category:1981\u201382 in Yugoslavian football]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[Yugoslav First League|Prva savezna liga]]\n| season             = 1981\u201382\n| winners            = [[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] (4th title)\n| runners-up         = \n| promoted           = \n| relegated          = [[FK Teteks|Teteks]]<br />[[NK Zagreb]]\n| continentalcup1    = [[1982\u201383 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers =  [[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n| continentalcup2    = [[1982\u201383 European Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers =  [[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]\n| continentalcup3    = [[1982\u201383 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers =  [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]<br />[[FK Sarajevo|Sarajevo]]\n| league topscorer   = [[Snje\u0161ko Cerin]] (19)\n| dates              = 26 July 1981 \u2013<br />2 May 1982\n| biggest home win   = \n| biggest away win   = \n| highest scoring    = \n| total goals        = \n| average goals      = \n| longest wins       = \n| longest unbeaten   = \n| longest losses     = \n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| average attendance = \n| prevseason         = [[1980\u201381 Yugoslav First League|1980\u201381]]\n| nextseason         = [[1982\u201383 Yugoslav First League|1982\u201383]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1981\u201382 [[Yugoslav First League]] season''' was the 36th season of the First Federal League ({{lang-sh|Prva savezna liga}}), the top level [[association football]] competition of [[SFR Yugoslavia]], since its establishment in 1946. The season began on 26 July 1981 and ended on 2 May 1982. [[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] led by [[Miroslav Bla\u017eevi\u0107]] won their fourth title five points ahead of [[1980\u201381 Yugoslav First League|previous season]]'s champions [[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]].\n\n==Teams==\nA total of eighteen teams contested the league, including sixteen sides from the [[1980\u201381 Yugoslav First League|1980\u201381 season]] and two sides promoted from the 1980\u201381 [[Yugoslav Second League]] (YSL) as winners of the two second level divisions East and West. The league was contested in a [[double round robin]] format, with each club playing every other club twice, for a total of 34 rounds. Two points were awarded for wins and one point for draws.\n\n[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac Banja Luka]] and [[FK Napredak Kru\u0161evac|Napredak Kru\u0161evac]] were relegated from the [[1980\u201381 Yugoslav First League]] after finishing the season in bottom two places of the league table. The two clubs promoted to top level were [[NK Osijek|Osijek]] and [[FK Teteks|Teteks Tetovo]].\n\n{{Location map+ |Yugoslavia |float=right |width=350 |caption=Locations of teams' home cities in the 1981\u201382 Yugoslav First League |places=\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=44.820556 |long=20.462222 |label=[[Belgrade]] |position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |la