{"title_page": "Stra\u017eisko", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name=Stra\u017eisko\n|settlement_type=Municipality\n|image_skyline = Kostel And\u011bl\u016f Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fdch v kontextu obce, Stra\u017eisko, okres Prost\u011bjov.jpg\n|image_caption = Church of the Guardian Angels over the village\n|image_shield=Stra\u017eisko CoA.jpg\n|image_flag=Stra\u017eisko flag.gif\n|subdivision_type=Country\n|subdivision_name={{CZE}}\n|subdivision_type1=[[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1=[[Olomouc Region|Olomouc]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n|subdivision_name2=[[Prost\u011bjov District|Prost\u011bjov]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|49|32|26|N|16|55|51|E|region:CZ|display=inline,title}}\n|pushpin_map=Czech Republic|area_total_km2=3.54\n|population_total=433|population_as_of=2006\n|population_density_km2=auto\n|elevation_m=407\n|postal_code_type=Postal&nbsp;code|postal_code=798&nbsp;44\n}}\n\n'''Stra\u017eisko''' is a village and municipality (''[[obec]]'') in [[Prost\u011bjov District]] in the [[Olomouc Region]] of the Czech Republic.\n\nThe municipality covers an area of {{convert|3.54|km2|sqmi}}, and has a population of 433 (as at 28&nbsp;August 2006).\n\nStra\u017eisko lies approximately {{convert|16|km|mi|0}} north-west of [[Prost\u011bjov]], {{convert|24|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} west of [[Olomouc]], and {{convert|191|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} east of [[Prague]].\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Stra\u017eisko}}\n*[http://www.olomouc.czso.cz/lexikon/mos_vdb.nsf/okresy/CZ0713/ Olomouc Regional Statistical Office: Municipalities of Prost\u011bjov District]\n\n{{Prost\u011bjov District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strazisko}}\n[[Category:Villages in Prost\u011bjov District]]\n\n\n{{Olomouc-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name=Stra\u017eisko\n|settlement_type=Municipality\n|image_skyline = Kostel And\u011bl\u016f Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fdch v kontextu obce, Stra\u017eisko, okres Prost\u011bjov.jpg\n|image_caption = Church of the Guardian Angels over the village\n|image_shield=Stra\u017eisko CoA.jpg\n|image_flag=Stra\u017eisko flag.gif\n|subdivision_type=Country\n|subdivision_name={{CZE}}\n|subdivision_type1=[[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1=[[Olomouc Region|Olomouc]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n|subdivision_name2=[[Prost\u011bjov District|Prost\u011bjov]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|49|32|26|N|16|55|51|E|region:CZ|display=inline,title}}\n|pushpin_map=Czech Republic|area_total_km2=3.54\n|population_total=433|population_as_of=2006\n|population_density_km2=auto\n|elevation_m=407\n|postal_code_type=Postal&nbsp;code|postal_code=798&nbsp;44\n}}\n\n'''Stra\u017eisko''' is a village and municipality (''[[obec]]'') in [[Prost\u011bjov District]] in the [[Olomouc Region]] of the Czech Republic.\n\nThe municipality covers an area of {{convert|3.54|km2|sqmi}}, and has a population of 433 (as at 28&nbsp;August 2006).\n\nStra\u017eisko lies approximately {{convert|16|km|mi|0}} north-west of [[Prost\u011bjov]], {{convert|24|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} west of [[Olomouc]], and {{convert|191|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} east of [[Prague]].\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Stra\u017eisko}}\n*[http://www.olomouc.czso.cz/lexikon/mos_vdb.nsf/okresy/CZ0713/ Olomouc Regional Statistical Office: Municipalities of Prost\u011bjov District]\n\n{{Prost\u011bjov District}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strazisko}}\n[[Category:Villages in Prost\u011bjov District]]\n\n\n{{Olomouc-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stra%C5%BEisko"}
{"title_page": "History of Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\nThe '''history of [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.]]''' began in 1901.  It first played in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]], and was elected to [[the Football League]] in 1920.  They won promotion to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] in the [[1978\u201379 in English football|1978\u201379 season]], but were relegated in the [[1982\u201383 in English football|1982\u201383 season]]. They returned to the top flight for the [[2017\u201318 in English football|2017\u201318 season]] playing in the [[Premier League]].\n\nThe club played its matches at the [[Goldstone Ground]] between 1902 and 1997. After the stadium was sold, the club played at Gillingham for two years, then at [[Withdean Stadium]] between 1999 and 2011. In 2011, a new stadium [[Falmer Stadium]] was completed and it has served as the home ground for the club since.\n\n== Formation ==\n[[File:Brighton & Hove Albion 1910.jpg|thumb|right|The 1910 team who beat Aston Villa to lift the FA Charity Shield]]\nThe club was first formed as Brighton & Hove United on 24 June 1901, and the name was quickly changed to [[Brighton & Hove Albion]].  The club took the place of a defunct club, Brighton & Hove Rangers, in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]].<ref name=\"beautifulhistory\">{{cite web |url=https://thebeautifulhistory.wordpress.com/clubs/brighton-hove-albion/ |title= Brighton & Hove Albion|work=The Beautiful History }}</ref> In the Southern League they won their only national honour to date, the [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]], by defeating Football League Champions [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in 1910.<ref>[http://www.talkfootball.co.uk/guides/brighton_and_hove_albion_history.html Brighton & Hove Albion] ''Talk Football''. Retrieved 9 August 2011</ref> There had previously been Old Brightonians, representing the area in the FA Cup in the 19th Century. \n\nThe club initially played at the Hove County Ground, with a few games were also at Goldstone Ground that was used by Hove F.C. From 1902 onwards, Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. and Hove F.C. shared the [[Goldstone Ground]].<ref name=\"beautifulhistory\"/>\n \nIn 1920, 19 years after the club was formed, they were elected to [[the Football League]]'s new [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]].\n\n== Crest history ==\nThe first known crest (1946\u20131975) to be used by Brighton & Hove Albion was the traditional coat-of-arms design of the twin towns of [[Brighton and Hove]]. A hybrid design employing the shield of Hove and the dolphin crest of Brighton was also used at times while a calligraphic shield was worn on the team shirts in the latter 1950s.\nDuring the 1974/75 season the club became known as 'The Dolphins' and by the beginning of the following season, a new club crest had been introduced.\nBoth this nickname and crest were to prove short-lived, however, following an incident said to have taken place in the Bo'sun public house in Brighton. Prior to a 'derby' fixture with fierce rivals, Crystal Palace, a few away supporters started chanting, \"Eagles, Eagles\" to which a group of Brighton & Hove Albion fans responded with a chant of \"Seagulls, Seagulls\". Current club director, Derek Chapman, is said to have been among the group who first christened the club with this nickname. The club has been known as 'The Seagulls' ever since and in 1977 the club crest was changed once again to represent this.<ref>{{cite news|last=Burnton|first=Simon|title=How Brighton v Crystal Palace grew into an unlikely rivalry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/football-league-blog/2011/sep/27/brighton-crystal-palace-rivalry|accessdate=11 November 2013|newspaper=Guardian|date=27 September 2011}}</ref>  A round seagull crest was used on club shirts until 1998 when the current design was introduced. New chairman Dick Knight wanted to sweep away all the remnants of the old, disgraced regime and saw an updated crest as a sign to supporters of new beginnings and happier times ahead.\n\nDuring the 2001/02 season, however, the club shirts displayed no seagull crest at all. For the club's centenary season a return was made to the traditional shields of the former boroughs of Brighton and Hove (now officially one city).\nThe Brighton shield shows [[Martlet]]s (birds used often in [[Sussex]] heraldry) and [[coral]] which both represent the sea. The [[Hove]] shield also displays martlets and a ship that has run ashore, representing a French galley, commemorating the French attacks on the coast of Hove during the early 16th century.\n\n==Mike Bamber==\n[[File:Goldstone Ground - geograph-1220106.jpg|thumb|[[Goldstone Ground]] (1902 \u2013 1997)]]\nMike Bamber was the Chairman of Brighton from October 1972 until 1983. He famously brought [[Brian Clough]] to the club later that year and then appointed [[Alan Mullery]], who led the football club to the First Division in the 1978/79 season. He also appointed [[Jimmy Melia]] as Manager who led the club to their one and only [[FA Cup Final]] in 1983. After relegation in the 1982/83 season, Mike Bamber stood down after the most dramatic 11 years in Brighton & Hove Albion's history.\n\n===Brian Clough and Peter Taylor===\nFollowing resignation from First Division [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] Brian Clough and his assistant [[Peter Taylor (footballer, born 1928)|Peter Taylor]] were persuaded by chairman [[Mike Bamber]] to join Brighton, who were then at the foot of the Third Division. Such was the loyalty to Clough that along with himself and Taylor, scouts and backroom staff completed the walk out, following the pair for their brief spell with Brighton.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1576977.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; Obituary: Brian Clough |publisher=BBC News  |date=20 September 2004 |accessdate=11 July 2009}}</ref> He proved less successful on the South Coast than with his previous club, winning only 12 of his 32 games in charge of the [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] side. Whereas eight months earlier Clough was managing a team playing Juventus in the European Cup, he was now managing a club who, just after his appointment as manager, lost to [[Walton & Hersham F.C.|Walton & Hersham]] 4\u20130 at home in an FA Cup replay. On 1 December 1973, his side lost 8\u20132 at home to [[Bristol Rovers]]. Albion eventually finished in 19th place that season. Clough left Brighton less than a year after his appointment, in July 1974, to become manager of [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] following [[Don Revie]]'s departure to become manager of [[England national football team|England]], though this time Taylor did not join him. Taylor remained for a further two seasons, guiding the team to a 4th-place finish in [[1975\u201376 in English football|1975\u201376]].\n\n===Life at the top (1979\u201383)===\nBrighton's life as a [[the Football League|Football League]] club brought little in the way of success and headlines until 1979, when under the management of former England player [[Alan Mullery]] they were [[Promotion and relegation|promoted]] to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] as [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] [[runners-up]].\n\nIn their first top-flight season, a 4\u20130 home defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] set the tone for an abysmal start to life in the big time. However, an away win to European Cup holders [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] inspired a remarkable recovery and Brighton finished the season well safe from relegation with a respectable 37 points.\n\nThe following season, Brighton found themselves in relegation trouble before an end-of-season rally with wins in the last four games saw them to safety. However, Mullery resigned after a dispute with Mike Bamber over the transfer of [[Mark Lawrenson]] and proposed changes to his coaching staff. He was replaced by [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] manager [[Mike Bailey (footballer)|Mike Bailey]].<ref name=\"pye\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/that-1980s-sports-blog/2017/may/25/brighton-top-flight-fa-cup-final |title=When Brighton last played in the top flight \u2013 and the FA Cup final \u2013 34 years ago |first=Steven |last=Pye |date=25 May 2017 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nSeason 1981-82 was the high point of Brighton's stay in the top flight, with the side in the top half or mid-table all season, finishing a credible 13th on 52 points, their highest-ever league finish to date. The following season saw a wildly inconsistent start, with victories over Arsenal and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] mixed in with heavy defeats and poor results in away games, and Mike Bailey eventually lost his job at the start of December 1982. [[Jimmy Melia]] and coach George Aitken took over on a temporary basis, later Melia was made permanent manager.  Melia however was unable to turn the situation around and Brighton ended up being relegated after a defeat at home to Manchester City, and finished the season in bottom place.<ref name=\"pye\"/>\n\nDespite their relegation, Brighton reached their first (and only to date) [[FA Cup]] final and drew 2\u20132 with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the first match. Brighton's goals were scored by Gordon Smith and Gary Stevens. This was the final that featured the \"miss\" by [[Gordon Smith (footballer born December 1954)|Gordon Smith]] with virtually the last kick of the game in extra time prompting the well known phrase \"and Smith must score\" - in effect it was actually a save by the Manchester United goalkeeper, [[Gary Bailey]]. In the replay Manchester United won 4\u20130, despite Brighton dominating the first twenty minutes of the match.\n\n===Sliding towards another relegation (1983\u201387)===\n\nBrighton's first Second Division campaign for four years began with a three straight defeats, but then things perked up with a run of five games unbeaten, including an amazing 7\u20130 victory over Charlton. However, another run of three defeats was enough to cost Melia his job, with former player [[Chris Cattlin]] stepping up to replace him and steering Brighton to mid-table safety. 1984-85 saw Brighton nearly return to the top flight, missing out on promotion by only two points. However, the following season saw Brighton slump to 11th place which, along with purported complaints from the players about Cattlin's management style, caused the board to axe him in favour of returning hero Alan Mullery. However, Mullery resigned at the start of 1987 due to a combination of indifferent form and unhappiness over the club's financial situation, and after his resignation Brighton would only win two more games all season, resulting in them being relegated again \u2014 this time to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]].\n\n===A brief revival (1987\u201391)===\nAlthough new manager [[Barry Lloyd]] hadn't been able to save Brighton's [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] status, he helped them regain it at the first time of asking. In 1990\u201391 Brighton spent the season pushing for [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] and finished sixth. They reached the play-off final after beating [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] 4\u20131 at home and 2\u20131 away but lost to [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] in the final at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] 3\u20131. If the disappointment of missing out on a top flight was traumatic for Brighton supporters, it was nothing compared to the traumas that the club would encounter over the next few years.\n\n===Relegated twice more (1991\u201396)===\nThe club's fans were hoping for a push for promotion to the upcoming new [[Premier League]] for the 1991\u201392 season, but instead they watched their side battle against relegation. The battle was lost and Brighton started the 1992\u201393 season in the new [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]].\nAlong with relegation, the club were universally derided for their playing strip at this time, which consisted of striped shirts and shorts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Room 101 The Worst Kits Ever|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Brighton_and_Hove_Albion/images/brighton___hove_albion_1991-1993-bo.gif|work=Historical Football Kits|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBarry Lloyd quit in December 1993, having failed to mount a serious challenge for promotion to [[Football League First Division|Division One]], and was replaced by [[Liam Brady]]. Brady lasted just two years before being replaced by [[Jimmy Case]], but the transition came too late to prevent Brighton from going down to [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] at the end of the 1995\u201396 season.\n\nMeanwhile, the club's financial situation was becoming increasingly precarious and the club's directors had come to a decision that the [[Goldstone Ground]] would have to be sold in order to pay off some of the club's huge debts.\n\n===Near oblivion (1996\u201398)===\n[[Jimmy Case]] was sacked after a terrible start to 1996\u201397 saw Brighton stuck the bottom of the league by a considerable margin \u2014 they seemed certain to be relegated from the Football League just 14 years after they had almost won the [[FA Cup]]. The club's directors appointed a relative unknown in [[Steve Gritt]], the former joint manager of [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], in hope of performing a miracle survival.\n\nBrighton's league form steadily improved under Gritt, although their improving chances of survival were put under further threat by a two-point deduction imposed as punishment for a pitch invasion by fans who were protesting against the sale of the [[Goldstone Ground|Goldstone]] ground.\n\n==Dick Knight==\n\n===Steve Gritt===\nBy the last day of the season, after being 13 points adrift at one stage they were off the bottom of the table and had to play the team directly below them, [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] \u2014 the game was in their hands. If Brighton won or drew, they would be safe. Brighton defender [[Kerry Mayo]] scored an own goal in the first half and it looked as though their 77-year league career was over. But a late goal saved the day and Brighton retained their league status on goals scored (despite Hereford's superior goal difference, since goals scored took precedence in the Football League at the time). Robbie Reinelt scored the goal that will write his place in Albion history, and in the process ending Hereford's 25-year league career as it was relegated to [[National League (English football)|Conference]].<ref name=\"hayward\"/>\n\nThe sale of the Goldstone ground went through in 1997 and this led to Brighton having to play some 70 miles away at Gillingham's [[Priestfield Stadium|Priestfield]] stadium.\n\n1997-98 saw Brighton endure more dismal form but they were never in any real danger of going down because [[Doncaster Rovers]] seemed set for the drop long before Christmas due to exceptionally dreadful form. But the board of directors wanted to move the club forward, and knew that they couldn't go on hoping forever that another team would do even worse than them. So Gritt was axed in February 1998 and replaced by former club captain [[Brian Horton]], who already had managerial experience with [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull]], [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and most recently [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield]].\n\nBrighton continued playing their home games at [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] for the 1998\u201399 season and were in contention for a play off place under [[Brian Horton]]. In January 1999 Horton left to join [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] as manager and  Jeff Wood was installed as the new manager of Brighton. With two wins and a draw in the first three games under Wood things continued to look good, however after picking up just 1 point from the next 10 games Brighton fell from play off contention and in April 1999 Wood was sacked. [[Micky Adams]] was appointed Brighton's new manager. Brighton finished the season in 17th place, their early season form enough to ensure they didn't spend a 3rd straight season fighting relegation to the Conference.\n\n===Back home (1999\u20132000)===\nFor the start of the 1999\u20132000 season The Seagulls moved back to Brighton and started playing their home games at [[Withdean Stadium]], a converted athletics track owned by the [[Local government in the United Kingdom|local council]]. The season started very well with Brighton born debutant [[Darren Freeman]] scoring a [[hat-trick]] in a 6-0 demolition of [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield]] in the first game of the season. Brighton's early season form was very patchy as they struggled to find consistency as a rebuilt squad struggled to gel. This early season inconsistency was carried over into the [[New Year]]. One bright point was Darren Freeman becoming the first goal scorer of the new [[millennium]] when he scored after just 2 minutes against [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] on 3 January 2000. In February 2000 Brighton signed a little known forward on loan from [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] called [[Bobby Zamora]]. Zamora made an instant impact scoring in his debut, the 1\u20131 home draw with [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth]]. Brighton lost their next game away at [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton]] 1\u20130, this was to prove their last defeat of the season as the following game a Zamora hat-trick inspired them to a 7\u20131 win at [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]]. Unfortunately the run of 8 wins and 6 draws came too late to mount a run at the play offs and Brighton finished 11, just 5 points off the play off places.\n\n===Promotion double (2000\u201302)===\n2000-01 was Brighton's first successful season for 13 years. They were crowned champions of [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] and promoted to [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]], where they made an excellent start and looked good bets for a second successive [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]]. Adams left in October 2001 to work as [[Dave Bassett]]'s assistant at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester]], being replaced by former Leicester manager [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]]. The transition proved to be a plus point for Brighton, who maintained their good form and ended the season as [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] champions \u2014 winning a second successive [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]]. Just five years after almost succumbing to the double threat of losing their [[the Football League|Football League]] status and going out of business completely, Brighton were one division away from the [[Premier League|Premiership]].\n\n===Another struggle (2002\u201303)===\n[[Peter John Taylor|Peter Taylor]] decided against renewing his short-term contract after the promotion triumph pursuing potentially bigger and better things at rich and up-and-coming club [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], so Brighton promoted youth team manager [[Martin Hinshelwood]] in his place. However, Brighton made a terrible start to the 2002\u201303 [[Football League First Division|Division One]] campaign, after winning their first game 3\u20131 away at [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] followed by a 0\u20130 draw against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry]] they set a record losing sequence losing 12 games in a row, including a 5\u20130 defeat by bitter rivals Crystal Palace on 26 October. Hinshelwood then became Director of Football and [[Steve Coppell]] was handed the manager's duties after the 10th defeat of the run. Coppell's spell started very brightly with a 2-0 half time lead against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], however some questionable refereeing decisions led to Brighton losing 4\u20132, the 12th and final defeat in the streak. Brighton stopped the slump by beating [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford]] 3\u20132 at [[Withdean Stadium|Withdean]] and continued to improve substantially under Coppell and looked as though they might be able to pull off a miracle survival. Although the great escape eventually proved beyond them, Brighton gained some satisfaction by staying alive until the last game of the season, a 2\u20132 draw at [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby]]. It was at the end of this season that [[Bobby Zamora]], who had been in the double championship winning side and top goalscorer during this period, was sold to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] for a \u00a31,500,000 fee.\n\n===Up and down again (2003-06)===\nCoppell moved to [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] in October 2003 and was replaced by [[Mark McGhee]], who had achieved [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] promotion success with [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] in 1994 and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] in 2001 \u2014 both times as [[champions]]. McGhee achieved promotion with Brighton at the first time of asking after a dramatic two-legged play-off semi-final against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon]] in which [[Adam Virgo]] headed an injury time equaliser in extra time to take the tie to 2\u20132 and a subsequent penalty shoot out which Albion won. This was followed by a 1\u20130 victory over [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] in the 2003\u201304 [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] play-off final (courtesy of a [[Leon Knight]] penalty in the 82nd minute) gaining them a place in the newly named Coca-Cola [[Football League Championship]] for the 2004\u201305 season. Albion finished 20th out of 24 clubs in the 2004\u20132005 season, narrowly avoiding the drop by a single point, but achieving their highest league position for 14 years. Brighton were relegated two games before the end of the 2005\u201306 Championship campaign after a disappointing season on the South coast.\n\n===Wilkins takes over (2006-08)===\nThe season began with uncertainty, over the future of manager [[Mark McGhee]] and consequently the out of contract players. Several board members, led by major shareholder [[Tony Bloom]] wanted McGhee sacked, but chairman [[Dick Knight (businessman)|Dick Knight]] still backed him. The situation was eventually resolved with McGhee retained as manager, youth coach Dean Wilkins promoted to first team coach, and first team coach Dean White named chief scout.\n\nWith pre-season came mixed messages, then manager [[Mark McGhee]] proclaiming promotion was the aim, while Knight stated at the pre-season fans forum that mid-table would be acceptable. The mixed feelings for Seagulls fans continued into the season, as new non-league signing Alex Revell scored a debut goal to secure a 1\u20130 victory at [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham]], but in the immediate aftermath young forward [[Colin Kazim-Richards]] handed in a transfer request that would eventually lead to him leaving the club on deadline day to sign for [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] for \u00a3150,000 with a 25% sell on clause.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~890386,00.html Albion Accept CKR Bid] ''Seagulls'', 30 August 2006. Retrieved 30 August 2006</ref>\n\nResults quickly deteriorated, and manager Mark McGhee was sacked at a meeting with Albion chairman [[Dick Knight (businessman)|Dick Knight]] on 7 September 2006. Assistant manager Bob Booker also left the club on the same day, after several years working with a number of managers. Knight cited a loss of faith in McGhee by fans in the previous season's relegation battle as one of the key reasons for his departure, as well as a loss of faith in the dressing room. Following McGhee's sacking the club installed [[Dean Wilkins]] as caretaker-manager. Chief scout Dean White was promoted to Wilkins' assistant manager. The pair were given the posts on a permanent basis on 29 September,<ref>[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~905209,00.html Albion Appoint Wilkins And White]. Retrieved 29 September 2006</ref> and former player [[Ian Russell Chapman|Ian Chapman]] was also added to the coaching staff shortly afterwards.\n\nIt was to prove a difficult season for the rookie management team, whose inexperience was mirrored by that of the team, 10 youth players having been awarded contracts in the summer [http://archive.theargus.co.uk/2006/3/10/208742.html], along with several youth team graduates already in the first team. There were some highlights - beating [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] 4\u20131 home and away, winning 2\u20131 away at [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] (one of only two home defeats for the eventual champions), and thrashing [[Conference National|Conference]] side [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] 8\u20130 at home in the first round of the [[FA Cup]]. A 3rd round tie away to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] was a break from League One for Brighton's fans, but their side were beaten 3-0 after a disappointing second-half performance. Albion also reached the Southern area Semi-Final of the [[Football League Trophy]]. January signing [[Bas Savage]] claimed cult fame on television programme [[Soccer AM]] for his moonwalk celebration following each one of his goals scored for the Albion, which were also proving crucial in keeping Brighton away from a relegation battle.\n\nThe [[2006-07 in English football|2006-07 season]] proved to be very successful for the Seagulls Reserve team, after securing the [[Sussex Senior Challenge Cup|Sussex Senior Cup]] and winning the [[Football Combination]] Southern League by finishing just one point ahead of [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton Reserves]]. On 24 April Dean Wilkins signed a three-year contract extension.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1015481,00.html Wilkins Agrees New Deal]''Seagulls''. Retrieved 23 April 2007</ref>\n\nThe [[2007-08 in English football|2007-08]] season was a considerably better season for the first team, who finished seventh in [[Football League One|League One]], finishing 7 points off the [[Football League One Play-Offs|play-offs]] and the club retained the [[Sussex Senior Challenge Cup|Sussex Senior Cup]] beating [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]], 1\u20130, in the final.[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1306227,00.html]\n\n===Shock exit and return of Adams (2008 - 2009)===\nAfter what many fans and pundits deemed a very good [[2007-08 in English football|2007-08 season]] for Brighton and [[Dean Wilkins]], it was announced on 8 May 2008 that Wilkins had been sacked from his position of manager and offered the role of first-team coach at the club, which he subsequently declined.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1329491,00.html Wilkins Leaves Albion] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 16 June 2008</ref> It was then revealed that [[Micky Adams]] would be returning to the club to take over the duties of being manager [http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1308744,00.html] and that [[coach (sport)#coaching staff|reserve team coach]] Ian Chapman had left the club. [http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1315784,00.html].\n\nThe 2008\u201309 season began strongly, albeit with poor home form. An early highlight was a penalty win against [[Manchester City]] in the second round of the [[Football League Cup]] which shocked the city fans and their new owner, the royalty of Abu Dhabi, Sheikh Mansour bin Zayed Al Nahyan. After being defeated by Luton on penalties in the Football League Trophy, Adams left the club by mutual consent.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11719_4954338,00.html Adams leaves Brighton]''SkySports''. Retrieved 7 August 2009</ref>\n\n==Tony Bloom==\n\n===Russell Slade (2009)===\nAfter 3 weeks of managerless football, Brighton appointed ex [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil]] manager [[Russell Slade]] as their frontman until at least the end of the season. Brighton lost their first two games under the management of Slade and like many seasons beforehand, it looked inevitable that Brighton would need a miracle to stay up - amazingly a miracle opportunity arose, with Slade winning 5 of Brighton's last 7 games. The relegation dogfight however lasted until the very last game, with a 1\u20130 win over [[Stockport County]], also risk of relegation following a 10-point deduction,<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/football_league/article6201717.ece Stockport on edge after entering administration | Football League - Times Online]''TimesOnline''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref> securing Brighton's position with just 2 points to spare. Brighton finished the season in 16th, and with a new manager, a new stadium under construction and a whole host of new signings over the summer, things were looking up for the team.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2008,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Fixtures | 2008]''Seagulls''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref><ref>\n[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/LeagueTable/0,,10433~20090615,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Table]''Seagulls''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref>\n\nAfter a poor run of results in the first few games of the  [[2009\u201310 Football League One|2009\u201310 season]], Slade was sacked on 1 November 2009.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/nov/01/brighton-sack-russell-slade   Guardian, Brighton and Hove Albion sack Russell Slade after just eight months]. Retrieved 1 November 2009</ref>\n\n===Gus Poyet (2009\u20132013)===\nThe former [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] player, [[Gus Poyet]], was appointed the new manager on 10 November 2009,<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/leagues/leagueone/brightonhove/6537516/Gus-Poyet-named-new-Brighton-manager.html   Telegraph, Gus Poyet named new Brighton manager]. Retrieved 10 November 2009</ref> with [[Mauricio Taricco]] as his assistant. Poyet won his first game in charge when the Seagulls overcame local rivals [[Southampton F.C.]] in a 3\u20131 victory at [[St Mary's Stadium|St. Mary's Stadium]]. Around this time, 12-year veteran chairman Dick Knight became Life President at the club to make way for [[Tony Bloom]], a fan of Brighton. The team gradually climbed up the league, owing to some large wins, including a 5-goal win at [[Wycombe Wanderers|Wycombe]], and 3 goal wins at [[Brentford F.C|Brentford]] and [[Tranmere Rovers F.C|Tranmere]], and despite an embarrassing 7-1 thrashing at [[Huddersfield Town]]. Brighton were able to retain their League 1 status on 24 April with a  win over [[Bristol Rovers]]. Brighton captain [[Nicky Forster]] left the club, and moved to [[Brentford F.C|Brentford]] after his contract expired at the end of the season. A late run saw Brighton go undefeated in 5 games, finishing the season 13th for the [[2009\u201310 Football League One|2009\u201310 Season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/LeagueTable/0,,10433~20100613,00.html | title= Brighton and Hove Albion |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110403051733/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/LeagueTable/0,,10433~20100613,00.html |archivedate=3 April 2011 |work=Seagulls |accessdate= 26 March 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2009,00.html   Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Fixtures | 2009] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref>\n\nIn the [[2010\u201311 Football League One|2010\u201311 Season]] Brighton's strong defence saw them to the top of the league, clear by 3 points, with the second greatest goal difference, only behind championship rivals [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], and to the most wins in the football league, equal to championship rivals Southampton.  They won promotion on Tuesday 12 April at the [[Withdean Stadium|Withdean]] after a 4\u20133 win over [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham and Redbridge]], the team then secured the League One title on 16 April at the [[Bescot Stadium]] after a 1\u20133 victory over [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]].  Brighton were undefeated, in cup and league, for over a year at the Withdean Stadium, with a total of 27-game run,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2010,00.html |title=Brighton and Hove Albion |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203213809/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2010,00.html |archivedate= 3 February 2012|work=Seagulls|accessdate= 19 July 2011}}</ref> and only lost 2 home games all season. During the season Brighton peak form included 9 consecutive home wins and 9 consecutive matches undefeated in all competitions and also recently recorded 8 consecutive wins, both home and away, equalling the post war record for the club. In addition, Brighton's 24 points in March matched the Football League all-time record for points in a single calendar month.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2010,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Fixtures | 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203213809/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2010,00.html |date=3 February 2012 }} \u201cSeagulls\u201d. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~2326713,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | News | Latest News | Latest News | Poyet Praise for History Boys] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 30 March 2011</ref> Brighton secured the League one title, and a victory parade was then held at the end of the season on Brighton seafront on 8 May 2011.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2009,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Fixtures | 2009] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/fixtures/default.stm BBC SPORT | Football | My Club | B | Brighton | Fixtures] ''BBC''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/results/default.stm BBC SPORT | Football | My Club | B | Brighton | Results] ''BBC''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/9014083.Albion_parade_starts_at_5_30pm_today/ Albion parade starts at 5.30pm today] \u2018\u2019The Argus\u2019\u2019. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref>\n\nAfter moving Brighton to the [[Football League Championship|Championpship]] as Champions [[Gus Poyet|Poyet]] started rebuilding after the loss 2 key players in the off season; [[PFA Team of the Year#League One 7|PFA Team of the Year]] player [[Elliott Bennett]] to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich]] for an undisclosed fee<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,,11741_6990798,00.html Blissful Bennett joins Canaries] ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref> and top scorer [[Glenn Murray]] to arch-rivals [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on a free transfer after Brighton failed to reach an agreement with the player at the end of his contract.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,,11741_6950187,00.html Eagles boss swoops for Murray] ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref> After these losses The Seagulls brought in many players, including [[Football League One#Top scorers|League One Top Scorer]] and \u00a32.5m club record signing [[Craig Mackail-Smith]]<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12875_7018601,00.html Poyet hails Mackail-Smith coup] ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref> and [[Kazenga LuaLua]] on loan for 3rd time, before purchasing him in mid-November.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12875_7041012,00.html Seagulls swoop for LuaLua] ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/9644186.stm Brighton & Hove Albion complete Kazenga LuaLua signing] ''BBC''. Retrieved 3 December 2011</ref>\n\n====New stadium====\n[[File:Amex Community Stadium.jpg|thumb| [[Falmer Stadium]], 2011 ]] \nBloom invested \u00a393 million<ref>[http://www.newsoftheworld.co.uk/sport/308704/TONY-BLOOM-ING-GOOD-Millionaire-poker-star-is-betting-on-Brighton.html   TONY IS BLOOM-ING GOOD]''NOTW''. Retrieved 16 May 2009</ref> after taking over in 2009 to secure the building of the new [[Falmer Stadium]] without the club taking external debt. The stadium was completed in 2011 and Brighton moved to [[Falmer Stadium]] 14 years gap after they left the [[Goldstone Ground]]. Brighton's first game, in the form of their reserve team, at the new stadium was a 2\u20130 win over [[Eastbourne Borough]] on 16 July 2011 in the [[Sussex Senior Challenge Cup|Sussex Senior Cup Final]].  Fittingly the first ever goal scorer at the stadium was [[Gary Hart (footballer)|Gary Hart]], who had been brought into the squad, out of contract, for one final game for the team, Gary Hart also scored the first goal at the Withdean Stadium after Brighton's moved there.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~2394383,00.html Albion Win the Sussex Senior Cup] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref> Brighton's first team took the field for the first time at the Amex against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] in a friendly on 30 July 2011.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~2405903,00.html Report: Albion 2 Tottenham 3] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 6 August 2011</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2011 Brighton played their first competitive game at Falmer Stadium against [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]], their last ever opponents at the Goldstone Ground where Brighton won 1\u20130.<ref>[http://www.glaucus.org.uk/Albion20.htm Brighton and Hove Albion v. Doncaster Rovers] '' glaucus''. Retrieved 6 August 2011</ref> The opening game of the [[2011\u201312 Football League Championship|2011-12 season]] ended with a 2\u20131 win for Brighton, after a 98th-minute winner.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/table/default.stm The Npower Football League Championship: Table] BBC. Retrieved 6 August 2011</ref>  The first goal scorer in a competitive first team match at Falmer Stadium was Doncaster Rovers player [[Billy Sharp]], who scored in the 39th minute. Brighton player [[Will Buckley (footballer)|Will Buckley]] came from the bench to score in the 83rd minute, and then sealed Brighton's victory with another goal eight minutes into injury time.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14351901.stm Brighton   2 - 1   Doncaster] ''BBC''. Retrieved 6 August 2011</ref>  The second league game of the season was a 1\u20130 win over [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], a team they ground shared with for 2 seasons after losing the Goldstone Ground.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/paul-newman-green-experiment-begins-to-bloom-at-brightons-new-home-2333496.html   Paul Newman: Green experiment begins to bloom at Brighton's new home] ''Independent''. Retrieved 9 August 2011</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14368545.stm Brighton   1 - 0   Gillingham] ''BBC''. Retrieved 9 August 2011</ref>  Brighton's first loss came at the hands of rivals [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in a 1\u20133 defeat on 27 September 2011,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/14982392.stm Brighton   1 - 3   Crystal Palace ''BBC''. Retrieved 3 Dec 2011]</ref> which Poyet described as \u201cthe lowest [point] that you can come as a Brighton manager.\u201d<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~2465182,00.html Poyet's Lowest Point ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 3 Dec 2011]</ref> Brighton's fortune fluctuated, but they managed to put together the joint-longest unbeaten run of thirteen consecutive games in that season's Championship. The team finished the season in 10th place, their highest finish in the English leagues for over 2 decades, and the first season in which they finished higher than Crystal Palace since 1986.\n\nBrighton would face [[Premier League]] opponents 4 times across the season, twice against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/teams/brighton-and-hove-albion/results  results ''BBC''. Retrieved 11 May 2012]</ref> Brighton played Liverpool at Anfield for the FA Cup 5th Round, where they were thrashed 6-1 while scoring three own goals, two from [[Liam Bridcutt]] and one from [[Lewis Dunk]]. This broke the record for the most number of own goals in an FA Cup match.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17001835  Liverpool 6-1 Brighton ''BBC''. Retrieved 11 May 2012]</ref>  The conclusion of the season saw the club announce that Falmer Stadium would be expanded to 27,500 seats with a new tier constructed in the East Stand during the summer break with plans to expand to 30,000 capacity by the start of the 2013\u201314 season. \n\nBrighton finished in fourth place in the [[2012\u201313 Football League Championship|2012-13 season]], however they were defeated by Crystal Palace in the Championship play-off semi-final on 13 May 2013. A few days following the defeat, Poyet was suspended for an alleged breach of contract over his comments after the defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/brighton-hove-albion/10062910/Brighton-and-Hove-Albion-suspend-manager-Gus-Poyet-for-an-alleged-breach-of-contract.html |title=Brighton & Hove Albion suspend manager Gus Poyet for an alleged breach of contract|date=16 May 2013|work=The Daily Telegraph |author=John Percy }}</ref>  On 23 June 2013, Brighton put out an official statement stating that Poyet had been dismissed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/news/article/club-statement-230613-876708.aspx?pd=635076116820000000 |title=Club Statement ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 23 June 2013 |access-date=23 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927072522/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/news/article/club-statement-230613-876708.aspx?pd=635076116820000000 |archive-date=27 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Poyet appealed the decision on the grounds of unfair dismissal, but the club upheld the decision to release Poyet for gross misconduct.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/brighton-hove-albion/10183244/Gus-Poyet-loses-appeal-against-unfair-dismissal-against-Brighton-and-Hove-Albion..html  Gus Poyet loses appeal against unfair dismissal against Brighton and Hove Albion ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 November 2013]</ref>\n\n===\u00d3scar Garc\u00eda and Sami Hyypi\u00e4 (2013\u20132014)===\n\nOn 26 June 2013, Brighton appointed [[\u00d3scar Garc\u00eda Junyent|\u00d3scar Garc\u00eda]] as head coach; this was shortly followed by [[Charlie Oatway]] leaving the club by mutual, having spent 8 years as a player, and 3 as a coach, at the club.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23074868  Oscar Garcia named new head coach of Brighton & Hove Albion ''BBC''. Retrieved 11 July 2013]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23200239 Charlie Oatway: Brighton & Hove Albion coach departs Amex  ''BBC''. Retrieved 11 July 2013]</ref>  After 6 competitive matches in charge of Brighton, [[CA Osasuna]] requested permission to approach the newly appointed manager; Brighton denied this request.<ref>[http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8905160/  Osasuna have been denied the chance to speak to Brighton head coach Oscar Garcia ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 11 November 2013]</ref>  However, the team was defeated by Derby in the Championship play-off semi-finals (6\u20132 on aggregate), and Oscar Garcia resigned as head coach after the game in May 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/may/11/brighton-oscar-garcia-resignation-defeat |title=Brighton manager \u00d3scar Garc\u00eda offers resignation after play-off defeat |author=Jacob Steinberg|date=11 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\n[[Sami Hyypi\u00e4]] became the manager of Brighton & Hove Albion in June 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/313333.html |title=Sami Hyypia takes Brighton job |date=6 June 2014 |work=ESPN }}</ref>  Hyppia won two of his first four fixtures, but won only one further game in the next 18 league games, and he resigned in December 2014 after only six months in charge.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/dec/22/sami-hyypia-resigns-brighton-manager |title=Former Liverpool defender Sami Hyypia resigns as Brighton manager |work=The Guardian |author=Former Liverpool defender Sami Hyypia resigns as Brighton manager |date=22 December 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30497171 |title=Sami Hyypia: Brighton manager resigns after one win in 18 games |work=BBC Sport |date=22 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Chris Hughton (2014\u20132019)===\n[[Chris Hughton]] was appointed manager on 31 December 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30640697 |title= Chris Hughton named new Brighton & Hove Albion manager|work=BBC Sport |date=31 December 2014 }}</ref>  Brighton was only two places above relegation when he took over, but Hughton managed to stave off the relegation threat.  In the [[2015\u201316 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2015\u201316 season]], the team became a contender for promotion to the premier league. It had a 21-match unbeaten run at the start of the season, interrupted by a defeat on 19 December 2015 against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]. It was a record for the club, and equalled West Ham's post-war record of 21 unbeaten games set in 1990\u201391.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34914013 |title=How Chris Hughton transformed Brighton into promotion contenders |author= Rob Stevens|work=BBC Sport }}</ref>  Brighton however narrowly missed out on automatic promotion on goal difference that season,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36266323 |title=Chris Hughton: Brighton motivated for play-offs after missing out on top two |work=BBC Sport |date=12 May 2016 }}</ref> and then lost their play-off semi-final tie against [[Sheffield Wednesday]] (3-1 on aggregate).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-england-championship-idUKKCN0Y727W |title=Sheffield Wednesday into Championship playoff final |date=16 May 2016 |work=Reuters }}</ref> Despite the loss, Hughton signed a new four-year contract with the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11741/10287238/chris-hughton-signs-new-four-year-brighton-contract |title=Chris Hughton signs new four-year Brighton contract |author= Jefferson Lake|date=18 May 2016 |work=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n\n====Promotion to Premier League====\nThe [[2016\u201317 in English football|2016\u201317 season]] started well for Brighton, and the team reached the No. 1 spot in January 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38980613 |title=Chris Hughton: Brighton must deal with 'difficult' period in promotion race |work=BBC Sport |date= 15 February 2017}}</ref> Although the team suffered a brief drop in form later that month and in February, the club gained automatic promotion to the Premier League with a 2\u20131 win over Wigan over the Easter weekend in April 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11741/10841688/brighton-boss-chris-hughton-hails-wonderful-achievement-of-promotion |title=Brighton boss Chris Hughton hails 'wonderful achievement' of promotion |work=Sky Sports |date=17 April 2017 | }}</ref> This is only the club's second appearance in the top flight, and their first since the 1982\u201383 season after which saw them nearly falling into the [[National League (English football)|Conference]] in 1997.<ref name=\"hayward\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/04/11/brighton-booming-20-years-since-almost-destroyed/ |title=Brighton are booming but it's only 20 years since they were almost destroyed |author=Paul Hayward |date=11 April 2017 |work=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2017\u201318 season]], Brighton won their first ever Premier League game on 9 September 2017, beating West Bromwich Albion 3\u20131 with the first goal from [[Pascal Gross]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41133349 |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 3-1 West Bromwich Albion |work= BBC Sport |date=9 September 2017}}</ref> They also achieved their first victory against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] since 1982,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43186393 |title =Brighton & Hove Albion 2:1 Arsenal |date=4 March 2018 |work=BBC}}</ref> as well as beating [[Manchester United]] in a win that secured their survival in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/05/04/brighton-vs-manchester-united-premier-league-live-score-updates/ |title=Jose Mourinho lays into Manchester United players after Brighton secure survival with outstanding victory |first1=Sam|last1= Dean| first2= JJ |last2=Bull|work=The Daily Telegraph |date=5 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nBrighton started their [[2018\u201319 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]] with an away loss to Watford, but managed to score another home win against Manchester United in the following game.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/19/brighton-manchester-united-premier-league-match-report |title=Brave and efficient Brighton see off a poor Manchester United effort |first=Jacob|last= Steinberg |date= 19 August 2018 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>  The team hovered mid-table until a string of losses in the second half of the season saw them struggling to survive in the Premier League, but they managed to escape relegation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47994861 |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 1-1 Newcastle United |first=Saj |last=Chowdhury|work=BBC Sport |date=27 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/17619254.seagulls-safe-in-the-premier-league-for-another-season/ |title=Seagulls safe in the Premier League for another season|first= Andy |last= Naylor|work=The Argus |date=3 May 2019 }}</ref> They enjoyed a good run in the [[2018\u201319 FA Cup]], reaching the semi-final after beating [[Bournemouth F.C.|Bournemouth]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Brom]], [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], eventually losing to Manchester City by a single goal.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/04/06/manchester-city-vs-brighton-fa-cup-semi-final-live-score-latest/ |title=Early Gabriel Jesus goal maintains aura of invincibility for Man City as they scrape past Brighton into FA Cup final |first1= Sam |last1=Wallace|first2= Adam |last2=Hurrey|date= 6 April 2019 |work=The Telegraph }}</ref> The club, however, was dissatisfied with a 17th-place finish in the Premier League, and Hughton was sacked at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48251716 |title=Chris Hughton: Brighton sack manager after 17th-placed finish in Premier League |date=13 May 2019 |work=BBC Sport }}</ref>\n\n===Graham Potter (2019\u2013)===\nOn 20 May 2019, club chairman Bloom announced that [[Graham Potter]] of [[Swansea F.C.|Swansea]] will take over as manager after paying Swansea \u00a33m in compensation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48340989|title= Graham Potter appointed new Brighton manager after leaving Swansea |work=BBC |date= 20 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.}}\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.]]\n[[Category:History of association football clubs in England|Brighton and Hove Albion]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\nThe '''history of [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.]]''' began in 1901.  It first played in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]], and was elected to [[the Football League]] in 1920.  They won promotion to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] in the [[1978\u201379 in English football|1978\u201379 season]], but were relegated in the [[1982\u201383 in English football|1982\u201383 season]]. They returned to the top flight for the [[2017\u201318 in English football|2017\u201318 season]] playing in the [[Premier League]].\n\nThe club played its matches at the [[Goldstone Ground]] between 1902 and 1997. After the stadium was sold, the club played at Gillingham for two years, then at [[Withdean Stadium]] between 1999 and 2011. In 2011, a new stadium [[Falmer Stadium]] was completed and it has served as the home ground for the club since.\n\n== Formation ==\n[[File:Brighton & Hove Albion 1910.jpg|thumb|right|The 1910 team who beat Aston Villa to lift the FA Charity Shield]]\nThe club was first formed as Brighton & Hove United on 24 June 1901, and the name was quickly changed to [[Brighton & Hove Albion]].  The club took the place of a defunct club, Brighton & Hove Rangers, in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]].<ref name=\"beautifulhistory\">{{cite web |url=https://thebeautifulhistory.wordpress.com/clubs/brighton-hove-albion/ |title= Brighton & Hove Albion|work=The Beautiful History }}</ref> In the Southern League they won their only national honour to date, the [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]], by defeating Football League Champions [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in 1910.<ref>[http://www.talkfootball.co.uk/guides/brighton_and_hove_albion_history.html Brighton & Hove Albion] ''Talk Football''. Retrieved 9 August 2011</ref> There had previously been Old Brightonians, representing the area in the FA Cup in the 19th Century. \n\nThe club initially played at the Hove County Ground, with a few games were also at Goldstone Ground that was used by Hove F.C. From 1902 onwards, Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. and Hove F.C. shared the [[Goldstone Ground]].<ref name=\"beautifulhistory\"/>\n \nIn 1920, 19 years after the club was formed, they were elected to [[the Football League]]'s new [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]].\n\n== Crest history ==\nThe first known crest (1946\u20131975) to be used by Brighton & Hove Albion was the traditional coat-of-arms design of the twin towns of [[Brighton and Hove]]. A hybrid design employing the shield of Hove and the dolphin crest of Brighton was also used at times while a calligraphic shield was worn on the team shirts in the latter 1950s.\nDuring the 1974/75 season the club became known as 'The Dolphins' and by the beginning of the following season, a new club crest had been introduced.\nBoth this nickname and crest were to prove short-lived, however, following an incident said to have taken place in the Bo'sun public house in Brighton. Prior to a 'derby' fixture with fierce rivals, Crystal Palace, a few away supporters started chanting, \"Eagles, Eagles\" to which a group of Brighton & Hove Albion fans responded with a chant of \"Seagulls, Seagulls\". Current club director, Derek Chapman, is said to have been among the group who first christened the club with this nickname. The club has been known as 'The Seagulls' ever since and in 1977 the club crest was changed once again to represent this.<ref>{{cite news|last=Burnton|first=Simon|title=How Brighton v Crystal Palace grew into an unlikely rivalry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/football-league-blog/2011/sep/27/brighton-crystal-palace-rivalry|accessdate=11 November 2013|newspaper=Guardian|date=27 September 2011}}</ref>  A round seagull crest was used on club shirts until 1998 when the current design was introduced. New chairman Dick Knight wanted to sweep away all the remnants of the old, disgraced regime and saw an updated crest as a sign to supporters of new beginnings and happier times ahead.\n\nDuring the 2001/02 season, however, the club shirts displayed no seagull crest at all. For the club's centenary season a return was made to the traditional shields of the former boroughs of Brighton and Hove (now officially one city).\nThe Brighton shield shows [[Martlet]]s (birds used often in [[Sussex]] heraldry) and [[coral]] which both represent the sea. The [[Hove]] shield also displays martlets and a ship that has run ashore, representing a French galley, commemorating the French attacks on the coast of Hove during the early 16th century.\n\n==Mike Bamber==\n[[File:Goldstone Ground - geograph-1220106.jpg|thumb|[[Goldstone Ground]] (1902 \u2013 1997)]]\nMike Bamber was the Chairman of Brighton from October 1972 until 1983. He famously brought [[Brian Clough]] to the club later that year and then appointed [[Alan Mullery]], who led the football club to the First Division in the 1978/79 season. He also appointed [[Jimmy Melia]] as Manager who led the club to their one and only [[FA Cup Final]] in 1983. After relegation in the 1982/83 season, Mike Bamber stood down after the most dramatic 11 years in Brighton & Hove Albion's history.\n\n===Brian Clough and Peter Taylor===\nFollowing resignation from First Division [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] Brian Clough and his assistant [[Peter Taylor (footballer, born 1928)|Peter Taylor]] were persuaded by chairman [[Mike Bamber]] to join Brighton, who were then at the foot of the Third Division. Such was the loyalty to Clough that along with himself and Taylor, scouts and backroom staff completed the walk out, following the pair for their brief spell with Brighton.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1576977.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; Obituary: Brian Clough |publisher=BBC News  |date=20 September 2004 |accessdate=11 July 2009}}</ref> He proved less successful on the South Coast than with his previous club, winning only 12 of his 32 games in charge of the [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] side. Whereas eight months earlier Clough was managing a team playing Juventus in the European Cup, he was now managing a club who, just after his appointment as manager, lost to [[Walton & Hersham F.C.|Walton & Hersham]] 4\u20130 at home in an FA Cup replay. On 1 December 1973, his side lost 8\u20132 at home to [[Bristol Rovers]]. Albion eventually finished in 19th place that season. Clough left Brighton less than a year after his appointment, in July 1974, to become manager of [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] following [[Don Revie]]'s departure to become manager of [[England national football team|England]], though this time Taylor did not join him. Taylor remained for a further two seasons, guiding the team to a 4th-place finish in [[1975\u201376 in English football|1975\u201376]].\n\n===Life at the top (1979\u201383)===\nBrighton's life as a [[the Football League|Football League]] club brought little in the way of success and headlines until 1979, when under the management of former England player [[Alan Mullery]] they were [[Promotion and relegation|promoted]] to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] as [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] [[runners-up]].\n\nIn their first top-flight season, a 4-0 home defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] set the tone for an abysmal start to life in the big time. However, an away win to European Cup holders [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] inspired a remarkable recovery and Brighton finished the season well safe from relegation with a respectable 37 points.\n\nThe following season, Brighton found themselves in relegation trouble before an end-of-season rally with wins in the last four games saw them to safety. However, Mullery resigned after a dispute with Mike Bamber over the transfer of [[Mark Lawrenson]] and proposed changes to his coaching staff. He was replaced by [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] manager [[Mike Bailey (footballer)|Mike Bailey]].<ref name=\"pye\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/that-1980s-sports-blog/2017/may/25/brighton-top-flight-fa-cup-final |title=When Brighton last played in the top flight \u2013 and the FA Cup final \u2013 34 years ago |first=Steven |last=Pye |date=25 May 2017 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nSeason 1981-82 was the high point of Brighton's stay in the top flight, with the side in the top half or mid-table all season, finishing a credible 13th on 52 points, their highest-ever league finish to date. The following season saw a wildly inconsistent start, with victories over Arsenal and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] mixed in with heavy defeats and poor results in away games, and Mike Bailey eventually lost his job at the start of December 1982. [[Jimmy Melia]] and coach George Aitken took over on a temporary basis, later Melia was made permanent manager.  Melia however was unable to turn the situation around and Brighton ended up being relegated after a defeat at home to Manchester City, and finished the season in bottom place.<ref name=\"pye\"/>\n\nDespite their relegation, Brighton reached their first (and only to date) [[FA Cup]] final and drew 2\u20132 with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the first match. Brighton's goals were scored by Gordon Smith and Gary Stevens. This was the final that featured the \"miss\" by [[Gordon Smith (footballer born December 1954)|Gordon Smith]] with virtually the last kick of the game in extra time prompting the well known phrase \"and Smith must score\" - in effect it was actually a save by the Manchester United goalkeeper, [[Gary Bailey]]. In the replay Manchester United won 4\u20130, despite Brighton dominating the first twenty minutes of the match.\n\n===Sliding towards another relegation (1983\u201387)===\n\nBrighton's first Second Division campaign for four years began with a three straight defeats, but then things perked up with a run of five games unbeaten, including an amazing 7-0 victory over Charlton. However, another run of three defeats was enough to cost Melia his job, with former player [[Chris Cattlin]] stepping up to replace him and steering Brighton to mid-table safety. 1984-85 saw Brighton nearly return to the top flight, missing out on promotion by only two points. However, the following season saw Brighton slump to 11th place which, along with purported complaints from the players about Cattlin's management style, caused the board to axe him in favour of returning hero Alan Mullery. However, Mullery resigned at the start of 1987 due to a combination of indifferent form and unhappiness over the club's financial situation, and after his resignation Brighton would only win two more games all season, resulting in them being relegated again \u2014 this time to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]].\n\n===A brief revival (1987\u201391)===\nAlthough new manager [[Barry Lloyd]] hadn't been able to save Brighton's [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] status, he helped them regain it at the first time of asking. In 1990\u201391 Brighton spent the season pushing for [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] and finished sixth. They reached the play-off final after beating [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] 4\u20131 at home and 2\u20131 away but lost to [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] in the final at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] 3-1. If the disappointment of missing out on a top flight was traumatic for Brighton supporters, it was nothing compared to the traumas that the club would encounter over the next few years.\n\n===Relegated twice more (1991\u201396)===\nThe club's fans were hoping for a push for promotion to the upcoming new [[Premier League]] for the 1991\u201392 season, but instead they watched their side battle against relegation. The battle was lost and Brighton started the 1992\u201393 season in the new [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]].\nAlong with relegation, the club were universally derided for their playing strip at this time, which consisted of striped shirts and shorts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Room 101 The Worst Kits Ever|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Brighton_and_Hove_Albion/images/brighton___hove_albion_1991-1993-bo.gif|work=Historical Football Kits|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBarry Lloyd quit in December 1993, having failed to mount a serious challenge for promotion to [[Football League First Division|Division One]], and was replaced by [[Liam Brady]]. Brady lasted just two years before being replaced by [[Jimmy Case]], but the transition came too late to prevent Brighton from going down to [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] at the end of the 1995\u201396 season.\n\nMeanwhile, the club's financial situation was becoming increasingly precarious and the club's directors had come to a decision that the [[Goldstone Ground]] would have to be sold in order to pay off some of the club's huge debts.\n\n===Near oblivion (1996\u201398)===\n[[Jimmy Case]] was sacked after a terrible start to 1996\u201397 saw Brighton stuck the bottom of the league by a considerable margin \u2014 they seemed certain to be relegated from the Football League just 14 years after they had almost won the [[FA Cup]]. The club's directors appointed a relative unknown in [[Steve Gritt]], the former joint manager of [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], in hope of performing a miracle survival.\n\nBrighton's league form steadily improved under Gritt, although their improving chances of survival were put under further threat by a two-point deduction imposed as punishment for a pitch invasion by fans who were protesting against the sale of the [[Goldstone Ground|Goldstone]] ground.\n\n==Dick Knight==\n\n===Steve Gritt===\nBy the last day of the season, after being 13 points adrift at one stage they were off the bottom of the table and had to play the team directly below them, [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] \u2014 the game was in their hands. If Brighton won or drew, they would be safe. Brighton defender [[Kerry Mayo]] scored an own goal in the first half and it looked as though their 77-year league career was over. But a late goal saved the day and Brighton retained their league status on goals scored (despite Hereford's superior goal difference, since goals scored took precedence in the Football League at the time). Robbie Reinelt scored the goal that will write his place in Albion history, and in the process ending Hereford's 25-year league career as it was relegated to [[National League (English football)|Conference]].<ref name=\"hayward\"/>\n\nThe sale of the Goldstone ground went through in 1997 and this led to Brighton having to play some 70 miles away at Gillingham's [[Priestfield Stadium|Priestfield]] stadium.\n\n1997-98 saw Brighton endure more dismal form but they were never in any real danger of going down because [[Doncaster Rovers]] seemed set for the drop long before Christmas due to exceptionally dreadful form. But the board of directors wanted to move the club forward, and knew that they couldn't go on hoping forever that another team would do even worse than them. So Gritt was axed in February 1998 and replaced by former club captain [[Brian Horton]], who already had managerial experience with [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull]], [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and most recently [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield]].\n\nBrighton continued playing their home games at [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] for the 1998-99 season and were in contention for a play off place under [[Brian Horton]]. In January 1999 Horton left to join [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] as manager and  Jeff Wood was installed as the new manager of Brighton. With two wins and a draw in the first three games under Wood things continued to look good, however after picking up just 1 point from the next 10 games Brighton fell from play off contention and in April 1999 Wood was sacked. [[Micky Adams]] was appointed Brighton's new manager. Brighton finished the season in 17th place, their early season form enough to ensure they didn't spend a 3rd straight season fighting relegation to the Conference.\n\n===Back home (1999\u20132000)===\nFor the start of the 1999-2000 season The Seagulls moved back to Brighton and started playing their home games at [[Withdean Stadium]], a converted athletics track owned by the [[Local government in the United Kingdom|local council]]. The season started very well with Brighton born debutant [[Darren Freeman]] scoring a [[hat-trick]] in a 6-0 demolition of [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield]] in the first game of the season. Brighton's early season form was very patchy as they struggled to find consistency as a rebuilt squad struggled to gel. This early season inconsistency was carried over into the [[New Year]]. One bright point was Darren Freeman becoming the first goal scorer of the new [[millennium]] when he scored after just 2 minutes against [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] on 3 January 2000. In February 2000 Brighton signed a little known forward on loan from [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] called [[Bobby Zamora]]. Zamora made an instant impact scoring in his debut, the 1-1 home draw with [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth]]. Brighton lost their next game away at [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton]] 1-0, this was to prove their last defeat of the season as the following game a Zamora hat-trick inspired them to a 7-1 win at [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]]. Unfortunately the run of 8 wins and 6 draws came too late to mount a run at the play offs and Brighton finished 11, just 5 points off the play off places.\n\n===Promotion double (2000\u201302)===\n2000-01 was Brighton's first successful season for 13 years. They were crowned champions of [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] and promoted to [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]], where they made an excellent start and looked good bets for a second successive [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]]. Adams left in October 2001 to work as [[Dave Bassett]]'s assistant at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester]], being replaced by former Leicester manager [[Peter Taylor (footballer born 1953)|Peter Taylor]]. The transition proved to be a plus point for Brighton, who maintained their good form and ended the season as [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] champions \u2014 winning a second successive [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]]. Just five years after almost succumbing to the double threat of losing their [[the Football League|Football League]] status and going out of business completely, Brighton were one division away from the [[Premier League|Premiership]].\n\n===Another struggle (2002\u201303)===\n[[Peter John Taylor|Peter Taylor]] decided against renewing his short-term contract after the promotion triumph pursuing potentially bigger and better things at rich and up-and-coming club [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], so Brighton promoted youth team manager [[Martin Hinshelwood]] in his place. However, Brighton made a terrible start to the 2002\u201303 [[Football League First Division|Division One]] campaign, after winning their first game 3\u20131 away at [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] followed by a 0\u20130 draw against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry]] they set a record losing sequence losing 12 games in a row, including a 5-0 defeat by bitter rivals Crystal Palace on 26 October. Hinshelwood then became Director of Football and [[Steve Coppell]] was handed the manager's duties after the 10th defeat of the run. Coppell's spell started very brightly with a 2-0 half time lead against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], however some questionable refereeing decisions led to Brighton losing 4-2, the 12th and final defeat in the streak. Brighton stopped the slump by beating [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford]] 3-2 at [[Withdean Stadium|Withdean]] and continued to improve substantially under Coppell and looked as though they might be able to pull off a miracle survival. Although the great escape eventually proved beyond them, Brighton gained some satisfaction by staying alive until the last game of the season, a 2\u20132 draw at [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby]]. It was at the end of this season that [[Bobby Zamora]], who had been in the double championship winning side and top goalscorer during this period, was sold to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] for a \u00a31,500,000 fee.\n\n===Up and down again (2003-06)===\nCoppell moved to [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] in October 2003 and was replaced by [[Mark McGhee]], who had achieved [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] promotion success with [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] in 1994 and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] in 2001 \u2014 both times as [[champions]]. McGhee achieved promotion with Brighton at the first time of asking after a dramatic two-legged play-off semi-final against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon]] in which [[Adam Virgo]] headed an injury time equaliser in extra time to take the tie to 2\u20132 and a subsequent penalty shoot out which Albion won. This was followed by a 1\u20130 victory over [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] in the 2003\u201304 [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] play-off final (courtesy of a [[Leon Knight]] penalty in the 82nd minute) gaining them a place in the newly named Coca-Cola [[Football League Championship]] for the 2004\u201305 season. Albion finished 20th out of 24 clubs in the 2004\u20132005 season, narrowly avoiding the drop by a single point, but achieving their highest league position for 14 years. Brighton were relegated two games before the end of the 2005\u201306 Championship campaign after a disappointing season on the South coast.\n\n===Wilkins takes over (2006-08)===\nThe season began with uncertainty, over the future of manager [[Mark McGhee]] and consequently the out of contract players. Several board members, led by major shareholder [[Tony Bloom]] wanted McGhee sacked, but chairman [[Dick Knight (businessman)|Dick Knight]] still backed him. The situation was eventually resolved with McGhee retained as manager, youth coach Dean Wilkins promoted to first team coach, and first team coach Dean White named chief scout.\n\nWith pre-season came mixed messages, then manager [[Mark McGhee]] proclaiming promotion was the aim, while Knight stated at the pre-season fans forum that mid-table would be acceptable. The mixed feelings for Seagulls fans continued into the season, as new non-league signing Alex Revell scored a debut goal to secure a 1-0 victory at [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham]], but in the immediate aftermath young forward [[Colin Kazim-Richards]] handed in a transfer request that would eventually lead to him leaving the club on deadline day to sign for [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] for \u00a3150,000 with a 25% sell on clause.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~890386,00.html Albion Accept CKR Bid] ''Seagulls'', 30 August 2006. Retrieved 30 August 2006</ref>\n\nResults quickly deteriorated, and manager Mark McGhee was sacked at a meeting with Albion chairman [[Dick Knight (businessman)|Dick Knight]] on 7 September 2006. Assistant manager Bob Booker also left the club on the same day, after several years working with a number of managers. Knight cited a loss of faith in McGhee by fans in the previous season's relegation battle as one of the key reasons for his departure, as well as a loss of faith in the dressing room. Following McGhee\u2019s sacking the club installed [[Dean Wilkins]] as caretaker-manager. Chief scout Dean White was promoted to Wilkins' assistant manager. The pair were given the posts on a permanent basis on 29 September,<ref>[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~905209,00.html Albion Appoint Wilkins And White]. Retrieved 29 September 2006</ref> and former player [[Ian Russell Chapman|Ian Chapman]] was also added to the coaching staff shortly afterwards.\n\nIt was to prove a difficult season for the rookie management team, whose inexperience was mirrored by that of the team, 10 youth players having been awarded contracts in the summer [http://archive.theargus.co.uk/2006/3/10/208742.html], along with several youth team graduates already in the first team. There were some highlights - beating [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] 4-1 home and away, winning 2-1 away at [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] (one of only two home defeats for the eventual champions), and thrashing [[Conference National|Conference]] side [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] 8-0 at home in the first round of the [[FA Cup]]. A 3rd round tie away to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] was a break from League One for Brighton's fans, but their side were beaten 3-0 after a disappointing second-half performance. Albion also reached the Southern area Semi-Final of the [[Football League Trophy]]. January signing [[Bas Savage]] claimed cult fame on television programme [[Soccer AM]] for his moonwalk celebration following each one of his goals scored for the Albion, which were also proving crucial in keeping Brighton away from a relegation battle.\n\nThe [[2006-07 in English football|2006-07 season]] proved to be very successful for the Seagulls Reserve team, after securing the [[Sussex Senior Challenge Cup|Sussex Senior Cup]] and winning the [[Football Combination]] Southern League by finishing just one point ahead of [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton Reserves]]. On 24 April Dean Wilkins signed a three-year contract extension.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1015481,00.html Wilkins Agrees New Deal]''Seagulls''. Retrieved 23 April 2007</ref>\n\nThe [[2007-08 in English football|2007-08]] season was a considerably better season for the first team, who finished seventh in [[Football League One|League One]], finishing 7 points off the [[Football League One Play-Offs|play-offs]] and the club retained the [[Sussex Senior Challenge Cup|Sussex Senior Cup]] beating [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]], 1-0, in the final.[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1306227,00.html]\n\n===Shock exit and return of Adams (2008 - 2009)===\nAfter what many fans and pundits deemed a very good [[2007-08 in English football|2007-08 season]] for Brighton and [[Dean Wilkins]], it was announced on 8 May 2008 that Wilkins had been sacked from his position of manager and offered the role of first-team coach at the club, which he subsequently declined.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1329491,00.html Wilkins Leaves Albion] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 16 June 2008</ref> It was then revealed that [[Micky Adams]] would be returning to the club to take over the duties of being manager [http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1308744,00.html] and that [[coach (sport)#coaching staff|reserve team coach]] Ian Chapman had left the club. [http://www.seagulls.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~1315784,00.html].\n\nThe 2008-09 season began strongly, albeit with poor home form. An early highlight was a penalty win against [[Manchester City]] in the second round of the [[Football League Cup]] which shocked the city fans and their new owner, the royalty of Abu Dhabi, Sheikh Mansour bin Zayed Al Nahyan. After being defeated by Luton on penalties in the Football League Trophy, Adams left the club by mutual consent.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11719_4954338,00.html Adams leaves Brighton]''SkySports''. Retrieved 7 August 2009</ref>\n\n==Tony Bloom==\n\n===Russell Slade (2009)===\nAfter 3 weeks of managerless football, Brighton appointed ex [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil]] manager [[Russell Slade]] as their frontman until at least the end of the season. Brighton lost their first two games under the management of Slade and like many seasons beforehand, it looked inevitable that Brighton would need a miracle to stay up - amazingly a miracle opportunity arose, with Slade winning 5 of Brighton's last 7 games. The relegation dogfight however lasted until the very last game, with a 1-0 win over [[Stockport County]], also risk of relegation following a 10-point deduction,<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/football_league/article6201717.ece Stockport on edge after entering administration | Football League - Times Online]''TimesOnline''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref> securing Brighton's position with just 2 points to spare. Brighton finished the season in 16th, and with a new manager, a new stadium under construction and a whole host of new signings over the summer, things were looking up for the team.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2008,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Fixtures | 2008]''Seagulls''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref><ref>\n[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/LeagueTable/0,,10433~20090615,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Table]''Seagulls''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref>\n\nAfter a poor run of results in the first few games of the  [[2009\u201310 Football League One|2009\u201310 season]], Slade was sacked on 1 November 2009.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/nov/01/brighton-sack-russell-slade   Guardian, Brighton and Hove Albion sack Russell Slade after just eight months]. Retrieved 1 November 2009</ref>\n\n===Gus Poyet (2009\u20132013)===\nThe former [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] player, [[Gus Poyet]], was appointed the new manager on 10 November 2009,<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/leagues/leagueone/brightonhove/6537516/Gus-Poyet-named-new-Brighton-manager.html   Telegraph, Gus Poyet named new Brighton manager]. Retrieved 10 November 2009</ref> with [[Mauricio Taricco]] as his assistant. Poyet won his first game in charge when the Seagulls overcame local rivals [[Southampton F.C.]] in a 3-1 victory at [[St Mary's Stadium|St. Mary's Stadium]]. Around this time, 12-year veteran chairman Dick Knight became Life President at the club to make way for [[Tony Bloom]], a fan of Brighton. The team gradually climbed up the league, owing to some large wins, including a 5-goal win at [[Wycombe Wanderers|Wycombe]], and 3 goal wins at [[Brentford F.C|Brentford]] and [[Tranmere Rovers F.C|Tranmere]], and despite an embarrassing 7-1 thrashing at [[Huddersfield Town]]. Brighton were able to retain their League 1 status on 24 April with a  win over [[Bristol Rovers]]. Brighton captain [[Nicky Forster]] left the club, and moved to [[Brentford F.C|Brentford]] after his contract expired at the end of the season. A late run saw Brighton go undefeated in 5 games, finishing the season 13th for the [[2009\u201310 Football League One|2009\u201310 Season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/LeagueTable/0,,10433~20100613,00.html | title= Brighton and Hove Albion |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110403051733/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/LeagueTable/0,,10433~20100613,00.html |archivedate=3 April 2011 |work=Seagulls |accessdate= 26 March 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2009,00.html   Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Fixtures | 2009] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref>\n\nIn the [[2010\u201311 Football League One|2010\u201311 Season]] Brighton's strong defence saw them to the top of the league, clear by 3 points, with the second greatest goal difference, only behind championship rivals [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], and to the most wins in the football league, equal to championship rivals Southampton.  They won promotion on Tuesday 12 April at the [[Withdean Stadium|Withdean]] after a 4-3 win over [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham and Redbridge]], the team then secured the League One title on 16 April at the [[Bescot Stadium]] after a 1-3 victory over [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]].  Brighton were undefeated, in cup and league, for over a year at the Withdean Stadium, with a total of 27 game run,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2010,00.html |title=Brighton and Hove Albion |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203213809/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2010,00.html |archivedate= 3 February 2012|work=Seagulls|accessdate= 19 July 2011}}</ref> and only lost 2 home games all season. During the season Brighton peak form included 9 consecutive home wins and 9 consecutive matches undefeated in all competitions and also recently recorded 8 consecutive wins, both home and away, equalling the post war record for the club. In addition, Brighton's 24 points in March matched the Football League all-time record for points in a single calendar month.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2010,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Fixtures | 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203213809/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2010,00.html |date=3 February 2012 }} \u201cSeagulls\u201d. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~2326713,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | News | Latest News | Latest News | Poyet Praise for History Boys] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 30 March 2011</ref> Brighton secured the League one title, and a victory parade was then held at the end of the season on Brighton seafront on 8 May 2011.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Fixtures/0,,10433~2009,00.html Brighton and Hove Albion | Match | Fixtures | 2009] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/fixtures/default.stm BBC SPORT | Football | My Club | B | Brighton | Fixtures] ''BBC''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/results/default.stm BBC SPORT | Football | My Club | B | Brighton | Results] ''BBC''. Retrieved 26 March 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/9014083.Albion_parade_starts_at_5_30pm_today/ Albion parade starts at 5.30pm today] \u2018\u2019The Argus\u2019\u2019. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref>\n\nAfter moving Brighton to the [[Football League Championship|Championpship]] as Champions [[Gus Poyet|Poyet]] started rebuilding after the loss 2 key players in the off season; [[PFA Team of the Year#League One 7|PFA Team of the Year]] player [[Elliott Bennett]] to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich]] for an undisclosed fee<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,,11741_6990798,00.html Blissful Bennett joins Canaries] ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref> and top scorer [[Glenn Murray]] to arch-rivals [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on a free transfer after Brighton failed to reach an agreement with the player at the end of his contract.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,,11741_6950187,00.html Eagles boss swoops for Murray] ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref> After these losses The Seagulls brought in many players, including [[Football League One#Top scorers|League One Top Scorer]] and \u00a32.5m club record signing [[Craig Mackail-Smith]]<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12875_7018601,00.html Poyet hails Mackail-Smith coup] ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref> and [[Kazenga LuaLua]] on loan for 3rd time, before purchasing him in mid-November.<ref>[http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12875_7041012,00.html Seagulls swoop for LuaLua] ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brighton/9644186.stm Brighton & Hove Albion complete Kazenga LuaLua signing] ''BBC''. Retrieved 3 December 2011</ref>\n\n====New stadium====\n[[File:Amex Community Stadium.jpg|thumb| [[Falmer Stadium]], 2011 ]] \nBloom invested \u00a393 million<ref>[http://www.newsoftheworld.co.uk/sport/308704/TONY-BLOOM-ING-GOOD-Millionaire-poker-star-is-betting-on-Brighton.html   TONY IS BLOOM-ING GOOD]''NOTW''. Retrieved 16 May 2009</ref> after taking over in 2009 to secure the building of the new [[Falmer Stadium]] without the club taking external debt. The stadium was completed in 2011 and Brighton moved to [[Falmer Stadium]] 14 years gap after they left the [[Goldstone Ground]]. Brighton\u2019s first game, in the form of their reserve team, at the new stadium was a 2-0 win over [[Eastbourne Borough]] on 16 July 2011 in the [[Sussex Senior Challenge Cup|Sussex Senior Cup Final]].  Fittingly the first ever goal scorer at the stadium was [[Gary Hart (footballer)|Gary Hart]], who had been brought into the squad, out of contract, for one final game for the team, Gary Hart also scored the first goal at the Withdean Stadium after Brighton's moved there.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~2394383,00.html Albion Win the Sussex Senior Cup] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 19 July 2011</ref> Brighton's first team took the field for the first time at the Amex against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] in a friendly on 30 July 2011.<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~2405903,00.html Report: Albion 2 Tottenham 3] ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 6 August 2011</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2011 Brighton played their first competitive game at Falmer Stadium against [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]], their last ever opponents at the Goldstone Ground where Brighton won 1-0.<ref>[http://www.glaucus.org.uk/Albion20.htm Brighton and Hove Albion v. Doncaster Rovers] '' glaucus''. Retrieved 6 August 2011</ref> The opening game of the [[2011\u201312 Football League Championship|2011-12 season]] ended with a 2-1 win for Brighton, after a 98th-minute winner.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/table/default.stm The Npower Football League Championship: Table] BBC. Retrieved 6 August 2011</ref>  The first goal scorer in a competitive first team match at Falmer Stadium was Doncaster Rovers player [[Billy Sharp]], who scored in the 39th minute. Brighton player [[Will Buckley (footballer)|Will Buckley]] came from the bench to score in the 83rd minute, and then sealed Brighton's victory with another goal eight minutes into injury time.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14351901.stm Brighton   2 - 1   Doncaster] ''BBC''. Retrieved 6 August 2011</ref>  The second league game of the season was a 1-0 win over [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], a team they ground shared with for 2 seasons after losing the Goldstone Ground.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/paul-newman-green-experiment-begins-to-bloom-at-brightons-new-home-2333496.html   Paul Newman: Green experiment begins to bloom at Brighton's new home] ''Independent''. Retrieved 9 August 2011</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14368545.stm Brighton   1 - 0   Gillingham] ''BBC''. Retrieved 9 August 2011</ref>  Brighton's first loss came at the hands of rivals [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in a 1-3 defeat on 27 September 2011,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/14982392.stm Brighton   1 - 3   Crystal Palace ''BBC''. Retrieved 3 Dec 2011]</ref> which Poyet described as \u201cthe lowest [point] that you can come as a Brighton manager.\u201d<ref>[http://www.seagulls.co.uk/page/Latest/0,,10433~2465182,00.html Poyet's Lowest Point ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 3 Dec 2011]</ref> Brighton's fortune fluctuated, but they managed to put together the joint-longest unbeaten run of thirteen consecutive games in that season's Championship. The team finished the season in 10th place, their highest finish in the English leagues for over 2 decades, and the first season in which they finished higher than Crystal Palace since 1986.\n\nBrighton would face [[Premier League]] opponents 4 times across the season, twice against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/teams/brighton-and-hove-albion/results  results ''BBC''. Retrieved 11 May 2012]</ref> Brighton played Liverpool at Anfield for the FA Cup 5th Round, where they were thrashed 6-1 while scoring three own goals, two from [[Liam Bridcutt]] and one from [[Lewis Dunk]]. This broke the record for the most number of own goals in an FA Cup match.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17001835  Liverpool 6-1 Brighton ''BBC''. Retrieved 11 May 2012]</ref>  The conclusion of the season saw the club announce that Falmer Stadium would be expanded to 27,500 seats with a new tier constructed in the East Stand during the summer break with plans to expand to 30,000 capacity by the start of the 2013-14 season. \n\nBrighton finished in fourth place in the [[2012\u201313 Football League Championship|2012-13 season]], however they were defeated by Crystal Palace in the Championship play-off semi-final on 13 May 2013. A few days following the defeat, Poyet was suspended for an alleged breach of contract over his comments after the defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/brighton-hove-albion/10062910/Brighton-and-Hove-Albion-suspend-manager-Gus-Poyet-for-an-alleged-breach-of-contract.html |title=Brighton & Hove Albion suspend manager Gus Poyet for an alleged breach of contract|date=16 May 2013|work=The Daily Telegraph |author=John Percy }}</ref>  On 23 June 2013, Brighton put out an official statement stating that Poyet had been dismissed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.seagulls.co.uk/news/article/club-statement-230613-876708.aspx?pd=635076116820000000 |title=Club Statement ''Seagulls''. Retrieved 23 June 2013 |access-date=23 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927072522/http://www.seagulls.co.uk/news/article/club-statement-230613-876708.aspx?pd=635076116820000000 |archive-date=27 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Poyet appealed the decision on the grounds of unfair dismissal, but the club upheld the decision to release Poyet for gross misconduct.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/brighton-hove-albion/10183244/Gus-Poyet-loses-appeal-against-unfair-dismissal-against-Brighton-and-Hove-Albion..html  Gus Poyet loses appeal against unfair dismissal against Brighton and Hove Albion ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved 11 November 2013]</ref>\n\n===\u00d3scar Garc\u00eda and Sami Hyypi\u00e4 (2013\u20132014)===\n\nOn 26 June 2013, Brighton appointed [[\u00d3scar Garc\u00eda Junyent|\u00d3scar Garc\u00eda]] as head coach; this was shortly followed by [[Charlie Oatway]] leaving the club by mutual, having spent 8 years as a player, and 3 as a coach, at the club.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23074868  Oscar Garcia named new head coach of Brighton & Hove Albion ''BBC''. Retrieved 11 July 2013]</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23200239 Charlie Oatway: Brighton & Hove Albion coach departs Amex  ''BBC''. Retrieved 11 July 2013]</ref>  After 6 competitive matches in charge of Brighton, [[CA Osasuna]] requested permission to approach the newly appointed manager; Brighton denied this request.<ref>[http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/8905160/  Osasuna have been denied the chance to speak to Brighton head coach Oscar Garcia ''Sky Sports''. Retrieved 11 November 2013]</ref>  However, the team was defeated by Derby in the Championship play-off semi-finals (6\u20132 on aggregate), and Oscar Garcia resigned as head coach after the game in May 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/may/11/brighton-oscar-garcia-resignation-defeat |title=Brighton manager \u00d3scar Garc\u00eda offers resignation after play-off defeat |author=Jacob Steinberg|date=11 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\n[[Sami Hyypi\u00e4]] became the manager of Brighton & Hove Albion in June 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/313333.html |title=Sami Hyypia takes Brighton job |date=6 June 2014 |work=ESPN }}</ref>  Hyppia won two of his first four fixtures, but won only one further game in the next 18 league games, and he resigned in December 2014 after only six months in charge.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/dec/22/sami-hyypia-resigns-brighton-manager |title=Former Liverpool defender Sami Hyypia resigns as Brighton manager |work=The Guardian |author=Former Liverpool defender Sami Hyypia resigns as Brighton manager |date=22 December 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30497171 |title=Sami Hyypia: Brighton manager resigns after one win in 18 games |work=BBC Sport |date=22 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Chris Hughton (2014\u20132019)===\n[[Chris Hughton]] was appointed manager on 31 December 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30640697 |title= Chris Hughton named new Brighton & Hove Albion manager|work=BBC Sport |date=31 December 2014 }}</ref>  Brighton was only two places above relegation when he took over, but Hughton managed to stave off the relegation threat.  In the [[2015\u201316 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2015\u201316 season]], the team became a contender for promotion to the premier league. It had a 21-match unbeaten run at the start of the season, interrupted by a defeat on 19 December 2015 against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]. It was a record for the club, and equalled West Ham's post-war record of 21 unbeaten games set in 1990\u201391.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34914013 |title=How Chris Hughton transformed Brighton into promotion contenders |author= Rob Stevens|work=BBC Sport }}</ref>  Brighton however narrowly missed out on automatic promotion on goal difference that season,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36266323 |title=Chris Hughton: Brighton motivated for play-offs after missing out on top two |work=BBC Sport |date=12 May 2016 }}</ref> and then lost their play-off semi-final tie against [[Sheffield Wednesday]] (3-1 on aggregate).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-england-championship-idUKKCN0Y727W |title=Sheffield Wednesday into Championship playoff final |date=16 May 2016 |work=Reuters }}</ref> Despite the loss, Hughton signed a new four-year contract with the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11741/10287238/chris-hughton-signs-new-four-year-brighton-contract |title=Chris Hughton signs new four-year Brighton contract |author= Jefferson Lake|date=18 May 2016 |work=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n\n====Promotion to Premier League====\nThe [[2016\u201317 in English football|2016\u201317 season]] started well for Brighton, and the team reached the No. 1 spot in January 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38980613 |title=Chris Hughton: Brighton must deal with 'difficult' period in promotion race |work=BBC Sport |date= 15 February 2017}}</ref> Although the team suffered a brief drop in form later that month and in February, the club gained automatic promotion to the Premier League with a 2-1 win over Wigan over the Easter weekend in April 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11741/10841688/brighton-boss-chris-hughton-hails-wonderful-achievement-of-promotion |title=Brighton boss Chris Hughton hails 'wonderful achievement' of promotion |work=Sky Sports |date=17 April 2017 | }}</ref> This is only the club's second appearance in the top flight, and their first since the 1982-83 season after which saw them nearly falling into the [[National League (English football)|Conference]] in 1997.<ref name=\"hayward\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/04/11/brighton-booming-20-years-since-almost-destroyed/ |title=Brighton are booming but it's only 20 years since they were almost destroyed |author=Paul Hayward |date=11 April 2017 |work=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2017\u201318 season]], Brighton won their first ever Premier League game on 9 September 2017, beating West Bromwich Albion 3-1 with the first goal from [[Pascal Gross]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41133349 |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 3-1 West Bromwich Albion |work= BBC Sport |date=9 September 2017}}</ref> They also achieved their first victory against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] since 1982,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43186393 |title =Brighton & Hove Albion 2:1 Arsenal |date=4 March 2018 |work=BBC}}</ref> as well as beating [[Manchester United]] in a win that secured their survival in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/05/04/brighton-vs-manchester-united-premier-league-live-score-updates/ |title=Jose Mourinho lays into Manchester United players after Brighton secure survival with outstanding victory |first1=Sam|last1= Dean| first2= JJ |last2=Bull|work=The Daily Telegraph |date=5 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nBrighton started their [[2018\u201319 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]] with an away loss to Watford, but managed to score another home win against Manchester United in the following game.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/aug/19/brighton-manchester-united-premier-league-match-report |title=Brave and efficient Brighton see off a poor Manchester United effort |first=Jacob|last= Steinberg |date= 19 August 2018 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>  The team hovered mid-table until a string of losses in the second half of the season saw them struggling to survive in the Premier League, but they managed to escape relegation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47994861 |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 1-1 Newcastle United |first=Saj |last=Chowdhury|work=BBC Sport |date=27 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/17619254.seagulls-safe-in-the-premier-league-for-another-season/ |title=Seagulls safe in the Premier League for another season|first= Andy |last= Naylor|work=The Argus |date=3 May 2019 }}</ref> They enjoyed a good run in the [[2018\u201319 FA Cup]], reaching the semi-final after beating [[Bournemouth F.C.|Bournemouth]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Brom]], [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], eventually losing to Manchester City by a single goal.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/04/06/manchester-city-vs-brighton-fa-cup-semi-final-live-score-latest/ |title=Early Gabriel Jesus goal maintains aura of invincibility for Man City as they scrape past Brighton into FA Cup final |first1= Sam |last1=Wallace|first2= Adam |last2=Hurrey|date= 6 April 2019 |work=The Telegraph }}</ref> The club, however, was dissatisfied with a 17th-place finish in the Premier League, and Hughton was sacked at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48251716 |title=Chris Hughton: Brighton sack manager after 17th-placed finish in Premier League |date=13 May 2019 |work=BBC Sport }}</ref>\n\n===Graham Potter (2019\u2013)===\nOn 20 May 2019, club chairman Bloom announced that [[Graham Potter]] of [[Swansea F.C.|Swansea]] will take over as manager after paying Swansea \u00a33m in compensation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48340989|title= Graham Potter appointed new Brighton manager after leaving Swansea |work=BBC |date= 20 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.}}\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.]]\n[[Category:History of association football clubs in England|Brighton and Hove Albion]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 4-0 \u2192 4\u20130 (25), 27 game \u2192 27-game, \u2019s \u2192 's (2), 3-1 \u2192 3\u20131 (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Brighton_%26_Hove_Albion_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name= Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd\n|settlement_type= Market town\n|image_skyline= Kaple p marie pomocne 03.JPG\n|image_caption = Chapel of [[Our Lady of Help]]\n|image_shield= Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd CoA.png\n|image_flag= Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd flag.svg\n|subdivision_type= Country\n|subdivision_name= {{CZE}}\n|subdivision_type1= [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1= [[South Bohemian Region|South Bohemian]]\n|subdivision_type2= [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n|subdivision_name2= [[Prachatice District|Prachatice]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|48|54|N|13|42|E|display=inline,title|region:CZ_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n|pushpin_map= Czech Republic\n|area_total_km2= 49.63\n|population_total= 449\n|population_as_of= 2019\n|population_density_km2= auto\n|elevation_m= 834\n|postal_code_type= Postal code\n|postal_code= 384 43 and 384 44\n|website=http://www.strazny.cz\n}}\n\n'''Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd''', until 1955 '''Kun\u017evart''' ({{lang-de|Kuschwarda}}) is a market town in [[Prachatice District]], [[Southern Bohemia]], [[Czech Republic]] on the border with [[Bavaria]], [[Germany]].\n\n==Geography==\nStr\u00e1\u017en\u00fd lies in the valley below the Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd mountain (1,115 m) between two tributaries of the [[Vltava]] river, near the border of the [[\u0160umava National Park]] (Bohemian Forest), 834 m a.s.l. It is a border crossing into Bavaria, Germany and lies 20&nbsp;km south of the town [[Vimperk]].<ref name=tourboard>[http://www.jiznicechy.org/en/index.php?path=mest/strazny.htm Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd] South Bohemian Region Tourism Information System, n.d., accessed 3 May 2018</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe village was founded at the end of the 17th century named Kun\u017evart, a nearby castle.<ref name=tourboard/> The village was called Kuschwarda by its residents, who were German-speaking. The town relied on farming and lumbering/woodcrafts, and its position as a border town. After the end of the Second World War, in 1946 the [[Expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia|residents were expelled]] to Germany, leaving behind their homes, farms and workshops, which were then given to Czechs. The 18th century Church of the Holy Trinity was torn down in the 1960s and all cemetery markers were removed, erasing much of the history of the town.\n\nIt grew in the second half of the 20th century through tourism and trade; it is noted for its casino and \u201cnightclubs\u201d. it is a winter holiday resort with ski-lifts on the surrounding slopes, like [[Kubova Hu\u0165]].<ref name=tourboard/>\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Karl Hoschna]], Austrian-American musician and composer\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.jiznicechy.cz/en/ South Bohemian Region Tourism Information System] (English)\n\n{{commons category|Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd}}\n{{Prachatice District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strazny}}\n[[Category:Market towns in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Prachatice District]]\n\n\n{{SouthBohemia-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name= Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd\n|settlement_type= Market town\n|image_skyline= Kaple p marie pomocne 03.JPG\n|image_caption = Chapel of [[Our Lady of Help]]\n|image_shield= Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd CoA.png\n|image_flag= Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd flag.svg\n|subdivision_type= Country\n|subdivision_name= {{CZE}}\n|subdivision_type1= [[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1= [[South Bohemian Region|South Bohemian]]\n|subdivision_type2= [[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n|subdivision_name2= [[Prachatice District|Prachatice]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|48|54|N|13|42|E|display=inline,title|region:CZ_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n|pushpin_map= Czech Republic\n|area_total_km2= 49.63\n|population_total= 449\n|population_as_of= 2019\n|population_density_km2= auto\n|elevation_m= 834\n|postal_code_type= Postal code\n|postal_code= 384 43 and 384 44\n|website=http://www.strazny.cz\n}}\n\n'''Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd''', until 1955 '''Kun\u017evart''' ({{lang-de|Kuschwarda}}) is a market town in [[Prachatice District]], [[Southern Bohemia]], [[Czech Republic]] on the border with [[Bavaria]], [[Germany]].\n\n==Geography==\nStr\u00e1\u017en\u00fd lies in the valley below the Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd mountain (1,115 m) between two tributaries of the [[Vltava]] river, near the border of the [[\u0160umava National Park]] (Bohemian Forest), 834 m a.s.l. It is a border crossing into Bavaria, Germany and lies 20 km south of the town [[Vimperk]].<ref name=tourboard>[http://www.jiznicechy.org/en/index.php?path=mest/strazny.htm Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd] South Bohemian Region Tourism Information System, n.d., accessed 3 May 2018</ref> \n\n==History==\nThe village was founded at the end of the 17th century named Kun\u017evart, a nearby castle.<ref name=tourboard/> The village was called Kuschwarda by its residents, who were German-speaking. The town relied on farming and lumbering/woodcrafts, and its position as a border town. After the end of the Second World War, in 1946 the [[Expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia|residents were expelled]] to Germany, leaving behind their homes, farms and workshops, which were then given to Czechs. The 18th century Church of the Holy Trinity was torn down in the 1960s and all cemetery markers were removed, erasing much of the history of the town.\n\nIt grew in the second half of the 20th century through tourism and trade; it is noted for its casino and \u201cnightclubs\u201d. it is a winter holiday resort with ski-lifts on the surrounding slopes, like [[Kubova Hu\u0165]].<ref name=tourboard/>\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Karl Hoschna]], Austrian-American musician and composer\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.jiznicechy.cz/en/ South Bohemian Region Tourism Information System] (English)\n\n{{commons category|Str\u00e1\u017en\u00fd}}\n{{Prachatice District}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strazny}}\n[[Category:Market towns in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Prachatice District]]\n\n\n{{SouthBohemia-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Str%C3%A1%C5%BEn%C3%BD"}
